segments.text: personal meeting with General Earl Rutter.
So Dr. Wooten just asked me, he says, Randy, do you have your uniform?
And I said, well, it was in my truck.
I mean, everything I own is in my truck.
And he says, if you're going to Vietnam, you need to see General Rutter.
And I kind of looked at him and I said,
The General Rutter, I guess I said, okay.
Well, it shows you how small the college was.
I don't know for sure in 69 what Dr. Wooten's position was.
He was just a really nice professor.
He was my advisor.
But he picked up the phone, and he called General Rutter's office, and he says, I was a first lieutenant then.
You were second lieutenant for 12 months, and then you were first lieutenant then.
And he says, I have First Lieutenant Randy House here.
He's a 67 A&M class of 67, and he's en route to Vietnam.
He leaves in three or four days, and I think General Rutter would like to talk to him.
Well, whoever was running General Rutter's outer office said, wait a minute, and the next thing we knew, we had an appointment like 45 minutes.
So I ran out, put on my uniform, and Dr. Wooten and I
marched up there, and I didn't even know where his office was, and he showed me where it was, and I went in there, and it was just the three of us.
And I'll never forget, he asked me a few questions, and I was a ranger, and I was in infantry, and airborne, and then he saw my aviator wings, and he said,
you're an airborne infantry ranger aviator.
And I said, yes, sir.
And he says, and you're only a lieutenant.
And I said, well, sir, they just, all I, except for a few months in the 82nd Airborne, I've just been in schools all this time, and those were just all the schools I went to.
And he says, you know, I was a ranger.
I said, yes, sir, I know all about the 2nd Rangers.
I said, I've read the books, and I can tell you everything about the 2nd Ranger Battalion.
And he says, well, so you're going to go to Vietnam and fly helicopters?
And I said, yes, sir.
And he said, well, the main thing about combat is taking care of the troops.
And he says taking care of the troops does not mean coddling them or babying them.
It means making sure they're trained and they're ready to
and they're tough and they don't quit but that you're out there sharing the hardships with them and you're not in some warm tent when they're freezing or
or you're dry when they're wet or whatever.
And he says, you know, that's the main thing that I can, and I don't remember, we talked for the longest time, but that's what I remember was he didn't talk to me about bravery.
He didn't talk to me about shooting straight.
He didn't talk to me about any of those skills.
It was taking care of the troops.
And so, yeah, my, everything that I remember about General Rutter as a student,
him moving it from a college to a university, him being the guy that saw that if it was gonna become a great university, it had to be coed.
And so in my unit, because General Rudder was in favor of it, and I thought General Rudder walked on water, I said, it's good that we're a university and it's good
that we have co-eds, but intellectually, I couldn't debate a good debater.
Because some of the guys had already figured out all the bad points of a university and co-ed things.
And all I could say was, the general wants this, and we've got to support him.
And I said, if we, and I remember telling the group, I said, if we fight this,
It's just going to make it harder.
It's going to happen anyway, but it's not going to be done as well.
I said, what General Rudder needs is our support.
And I remember just telling a group of people that, and I was definitely the minority.
All right.
What about making the Corps non-compulsory?
Well, that happened at the same time.
How did you and your associates feel about that?
Well...

it was interesting although I did not take the core seriously as seriously as I wish I would have or I could have or as I did a little later I felt the core was a good thing and I wasn't into intellectually the freedom of choosing so I was probably a pretty much of a traditionalist and I didn't see
the wisdom of that.
But I never, for some reason, I can't tell you what General Rutter's position was on it.
You know, I mean, at the time, I know what it is now.
I mean, I know he was a proponent of, you know, a university had to widen its vision blocks, but for some reason, he wasn't getting criticized or credited with that, and so I didn't.
What about integration, racial integration?
Do you know that before I got into the Army, I don't think I ever met, I did not, I wasn't ever in a football game, a situation, a classroom, anything with a Jew or a black.
But y'all were aware there were black students starting to attend A&M, weren't you?
Right, but I never saw one.
No, but what was the attitude?
See, I haven't uncovered so far anybody that thought that was bad.
No.
I was raised...
down here at this ranch, and the land we bought was in 1865 given to three slave families.
And when my daddy in 1955 bought this land, there was like 100 heirs to these families, these 1865 families.
And everybody, all my neighbors were black, and they were all good people.
And we all, you know, they helped me in the hay fields.
And I always felt, that's my fax, I always felt, you know, they were okay.
So I never had any negative black minority situation.
So I wasn't, I don't think I was prejudiced.
It's just that
In high school, they were just never there.

I remember as soon as I got in the Army and some of the things started happening with Martin Luther King and all that and the marches and all that started happening, I was glad to see, I remember being glad to listen that Martin Luther King was talking nonviolence because I felt even back then that if blacks became violent,
we were going to be in big trouble.
And so I was kind of a fan of Martin Luther King when I first started reading about his speeches.
But I don't remember integration being a big deal, not like women and not like going from a college to a university.
Let me turn this.
As a sophomore,
Anything unusual happen with academics?
Any major changes for you as a sophomore?
No, nothing stands out except I took organic chemistry, 227, 228.
and I made D's and Dr. Romaine told me that I would not be accepted to vet school.
I didn't know whether to believe him or not because I found entries where I even had my checklist of when I'm accepted to vet school, what I'm gonna do.
But I was not accepted to vet school at the end of my sophomore year.
You did apply.
I did apply, oh yeah.
I applied, matter of fact, I was an alternate.
And they went through like 18, they accepted 120 something.
And it turned to a three year program, three year around the clock.
And they upped it to about 120.
And I was like 18th alternate, and they went through around 15 alternates.
But I was very encouraged by that, and Dr. Romaine was.
And so that's when he allowed me to take, in my junior year, veterinary genetics and some veterinary courses.
And I don't know if it was out of the ordinary or whatever, but I took veterinary courses, and I made A's in them.
At the end of my junior year, I applied to vet school.
My grades were much better.
I had demonstrated I could take vet courses and make A's, and I wasn't even an alternate.
But what had happened was the Vietnam War had gotten serious, and most of those that were accepted at A&M were not pre-vet, but they were
they had their degrees, they had four-year degrees, and so it became what I felt was a dodge, you know, a draft dodge.
And so there's so many people applied, and they were still on except 120, and although I was doing better, I didn't even, you know, I wasn't even in the hunt anymore.
So at the end of my junior year, I knew...
that I wouldn't be a veterinarian at that time.
And then simultaneously with that, my brother had just gotten out of the Navy as an officer.
He was a Tulane graduate, had gone through Navy ROTC, had done his two years in the Navy.
and was in the Navy Reserves and chose to be in the active reserves in Houston and was in a CB company.
He was a company commander of a CB company in Houston, Texas.
Well, there was a, right at this time, there was the Department of Defense, and I've subsequently researched it, were debating, it was the,

butter and guns debate with Lyndon Johnson, and Lyndon wanted the Great Society program to continue, and he detested the war, but he was determined to fight it without the reserves and without the National Guard, which we had never done before in the history of this nation.
But some in the Department of Defense convinced somebody in the White House to do a test, so they called up one
reserve air force unit, one reserve navy unit, one reserve marine unit, one reserve army unit, and sent them to Vietnam just as a test to see how they would do.
Well, the unit they picked in the navy was my brother's unit, and he had just gone into business for himself as an architect in Houston.
He had a brand new business because he'd been working for an architect for a couple years, and now he's just gone into his own business
And he had three sons under the age of five.
And he gets called up and he's one month from the end of his seven-year, eight-year commitment.
I mean, one more month and he would have not been eligible.
And he didn't even blink.
He said, if that's the way it is, I'm going to Vietnam.
So here I am.
At the end of my junior year, my brother, who to this day is next to my dad, is the finest man I've ever met.
He was seven years older than me, was an honor student, an unbelievable athlete, president of his class, always the top-notch guy, and I was kind of in the middle of the pack in my group.
So here he was going to Vietnam, so I said, I'm going to Vietnam.
I mean, my big brother's going to Vietnam, I'm going to Vietnam.
So I went and talked to Colonel Simmons, Jim Simmons, my ROTC instructor friend, who was a captain then, and I said, well, what do you think we should do?
And he says, well, you've got to make a decision.
You said you didn't, you know, you went, you're...
Your junior year you went contract, so you're under contract, and so you're going to ROTC summer camp at Fort Sill this summer.
He said, what you need to do is you need to do real well at ROTC summer camp.
You need to come back your senior year and just get the commission as quick as you can.

and go to Vietnam, and then I said, do your duty, and he was an Aggie, Jim was an Aggie, and he says, then after that, you can either resign or stay in, and if you want to resign, try to come back here, and maybe then you'll be older, you'll be a graduate, you may be able to get into some kind of a master's program, and then be able to get back and be able to accept vet school.
Things may be a little different a couple years from now.
So I said, okay.
So I went to ROTC summer camp that year.
Where was it?
At Fort Sill, Oklahoma.
Tropical Oasis.
Yeah.
And it was really interesting.
Whereas Army ROTC at A&M was a lot of marching.
We didn't have the Rangers then.
We didn't do a lot of real Army stuff.
The rifle marksmanship was very focused and limited.
And so what I knew about the Army was drill and ceremony.
I get to...
Fort Sill, and you go on compass courses, survival, escape and evasion courses.
You have to shoot all kind of weapons.
I mean, pistols, rifles, bazookas.
You have to do all these things.
Well, I was a natural at all that.
And I came back from ROTC number one cadet in the program.
I wasn't even an all, I was, my senior year, I was not anything.
I was just a senior.
And I came out of ROTC summer camp number one.
Eddie Joe Davis was number 15.
All these guys that were... And so A&M didn't know what to do with me.
All of a sudden, they had this guy who had never taken ROTC very seriously, had made A's in all the ROTC courses, had never caused any trouble, but hadn't been...
You know, wasn't in the Ross Volunteers, wasn't in anything, you know.
All of a sudden, he's the number one cadet out of 1,700 at ROTC summer camp in all the whole nation, you know.
My, my, my.
And so it was really interesting.
One of the things I did up there was I maxed out the PT test.
All the PT tests I scored 100 on.
Well, so they said, we're going to put House in charge of preparing the juniors for summer camp.
So we're going to create a special position.
And he's not going to, you know, here at A&M.
And so my whole senior year, I had a special office, a special staff, and our mission was to prepare the juniors.
And so I started, I just took what we did at summer camp and started saying, well, we need to do these things.
Well, it had never been done before at A&M.
You mean you want to do a compass course?
And I says, yeah, you got enough land out here and you got gullies and whatever.
So I went out and built a compass course.
And I said, look, you do all this rappelling and stuff and it's fun.
And so I went and built a rappelling tower and qualified people in my whole senior year.
brought these kids through.
Well, I remember Gene Stallings was the football coach.
And I wanted to set up a PT test and an obstacle course where the football team practiced.
And this was not going to be a permanent thing, you know, but it was going to be semi-permanent.
And so I had to go see Gene Stallings.
Well, I'd never met him before.
And I went in, you know, I got an appointment and went in there because it was, you know, the land was at premium and this is where, you know, my analysis, I need to do this thing.
And I went in there and met him for the first time and he listened to me and he said, I heard what you were coming in here to ask and I was prepared to throw you out.
But he said, it sounds like you're really serious about this program.
And I said, sir,
You know, if I can run these kids through here in the spring repeatedly, I said, we'll knock them dead at summer camp next summer.
And I said, I'll have it all gone for spring training.
I mean, I'll have it all gone.
You can have all these fields.

and everything so he gave me permission to use the fields and then we went out there and I don't know where I got the money but we built you know with railroad ties and two by fours we built this obstacle course and so that was my mission and then you know then the kids went off and I think we did the Aggies
And ever since then, I've watched the ROTC summer camps, and the Aggies have done extremely well at ROTC summer camp.
They didn't necessarily do well before.
But now, even to this day, we have a junior preparation program, and that's what we needed.
Now, to whom were you turning for advice?
Jim Simmons.
Jim Simmons.
Yes, Captain Jim Simmons.
All right, but for you generally...
Academically.
Dr. Romaine had been.
And then Dr. Wooten.
And Aggie.
And Aggie, he was my advisor.
Did you, were you thinking about a, let's say as a senior, if you didn't get into vet school ever, what would your career perhaps be?
No.
All I was doing was going to Vietnam, serving my country, coming back.
And the only issue was did I come back and

I'd taken the GRE, so was I going to go to graduate school in ag-eco, or was I just going to start taking, somehow get permission to take vet courses and then just kind of work my way in, and I hadn't sorted that out.
But no, my whole life I'd wanted to be a horse doctor, and I was determined to be the best horse doctor around.
And academically, do you feel that you got about the grades you earned?
Oh, yeah.
What was really interesting, and my cousin taught this to me, but I didn't learn it, because my senior year, I made almost all As.
I really did well my senior year.
And my junior year, I did much better.
It was just that organic chemistry.
But my cousin, who went to vet school and was accepted, Texas A&M would take like seven Louisiana students
And they had hundreds applying, and he was one of those seven.
And this was a kid I was raised with.
Matter of fact, our birthdays are July 23rd and July 24th.
We're the same age, and our mamas are sisters.
And just a really close friend and close friend to this day.
I remember when Donald came here, I would study with Donald, because I was taking a couple courses.
And I'll never forget this.
I studied for the exam at the time.
Donald studied to know everything about the course, know everything about the subject.
He never studied for an exam.
And I figured that out, but I figured it out too late.
And so then when I went to all through all my courses, you know, in the Army, I was always an honor graduate in every course.
Every school I went to, I was a distinguished graduate of the Ranger School.
I was the first to solo in my flight class.
But my philosophy changed.
I no longer studied for tests.
I studied to know everything there was about the subject.
And then I just would go take the test.
And that's what Donald taught me, you know, as just a friend and a cousin.
And then it just, and then when I went to graduate school at Clemson, you know, the Army said, you know, we're sending you to graduate school.
You're representing the U.S. Army.
You've got to make all As.
And I was right out of Vietnam, and I said, yes, sir.
And I went to Clemson and made all As.
And I never made all As in my life.
As far as you and your buddies knew, were there any giveaway courses at A&M when you were an undergraduate?
If there were, I didn't know about it.
Or it didn't register because, like I say, the only advice from my dad was take the hard courses that make you think and make you write and make you communicate.
So I wasn't looking for easy courses.
See, I really didn't.
I was so confident I was going to get in vet school because I knew so much about horses and cattle that I figured that with...
You know, as long as I took the tough courses and I did okay.
It was just that organic chemistry that, yes, darling.
Back on.
As you look back, were there some courses that really were important to your future that you now realize you took as an undergraduate A&M?
And or some people?
Well, as far as individual courses,
I don't, I don't, a course doesn't stick out that I can say was, you know, that really made a difference.
I think I was guided enough, counseled enough that, that I,

Had a fairly broad base of courses and the only ones I remember were the ones I didn't do well in you know that I stumbled and then didn't and even when I read in my journals I Admit I just didn't work hard enough because it at that time in my life I
And it was always through the military.
I was just a hard worker.
And if I applied myself and I worked hard, then I got the results.
If I backslid a little bit, I wasn't smart enough to pull it off.
I wasn't gifted enough.
And so every once in a while, I'd get caught like that.
As far as people, it was interesting.
Randy Madsen was in his heyday.
He was my classmate.
He and I played handball, and here he was, the best athlete in the world, but I could hang in there with him playing handball.

I played handball for 30 years, and I learned, I took it in 63, and when you read through my journals, that seemed to be the thing that I really enjoyed, was playing handball, and it was an equalizer.
You didn't have to be the fastest guy in the world.
You didn't have to be the quickest.
You didn't have to be the biggest or the strongest.
You had to be in excellent condition, and I was in excellent physical condition.
That was always a hallmark of mine, even though I didn't have some of the other gifts.
So Randy doesn't remember it.
I've met him a couple times since then, and he doesn't remember us playing as much as I remember.
But see, I was just a nothing.
guy and he used to lift weights over there, you know, where the handball courts were.
And then I think just to relax a little bit, he'd go up and play handball.
Well, he wasn't a serious handball player and I was a serious handball player.
So I always, I was, but I thought Randy Madsen represented
Texas A&M in the Olympics, you know, and was just such a gentleman.
And I remember, you know, how some of the people stood on the platforms and wanted some of these things they said in the interviews.
And Randy was always such a class act.
And I was always impressed with that.
I knew Eddie Joe Davis all four years.
Describe Eddie Joe as a student.
Eddie Joe, you knew as a fish, was going to be the Corps commander.
And Eddie Joe Davis, what was interesting about Eddie Joe was Eddie Joe was a nice guy.
He was a nice person.
But he was just very focused.
And I always admired that about him.
I wasn't focused on the Corps.
I was focused on ranching and rodeoing and other things.

But I admired Eddie Joe, and I knew that he would do very well, and I was not the least surprised when he was my corps commander, and I was very proud that he was our corps commander, and I thought he was a great one.
Were there any notable visitors that came to A&M during that time?
I can't think of any Hollywood stars or the president or... No.
Oh, were you present in Duncan Dunning Hall when Linda Bird Johnson came to eat lunch?
No, if I did, it didn't register, so I wasn't.
While Lyndon was vice president, I think it was,
Yeah, this would be a year before you.
While Lyndon was vice president, he came to speak at SCONA.
Oh, okay.
And she came as a freshman from UT to come and hear her father speak.
The Corps commander took her over to Duncan Dining Hall, and this is the week after the massacre of the Aggies on Thanksgiving Day.
And on a given signal, all the fish jumped up and yelled, beat the hell out of TU.
She stood up in silence, and everybody got very, very quiet.
And then all at once, she gave a hook'em horn sign and yelled, hook'em horns, and they stood and cheered for her.
No, I don't remember anything like that.
What about MSC?
Was that important for you?
Were there MSC activities you participated in?
Well, there was a couple things about the MSC.
Number one, the Aggies that died in World War II, we ended up doing a Vietnam War kind of like that, where their names are all there.
And I remember...
frequently standing there just looking at those names and thinking about that, because Vietnam was happening, especially my senior year, because I knew I was going to Vietnam and everything.
So that was kind of interesting.
The second thing was I loved the Metzger gun collection.
It was at the time in the MSC.
And I just was fascinated that someone was
could acquire a personal collection of firearms like that.
And I would go up there, and there was hardly ever anybody there.
And so it was kind of a solitude place for me.
The other thing about the MSC was I could get, that's where I started learning to read the Wall Street.
And I've read the Wall Street ever since.
And I'd buy a Wall Street, a cup of coffee, and a donut for a quarter.
And there was a special, and this was when I was a junior and a senior, and I would read the Wall Street in the same place at the same time.
It seemed like the same place at the same time for two years.
And the MSC, you know, I liked it, you know, because, you know, even seniors couldn't walk on the grass.
I mean, it was a very special place.
I never saw any harassment going on there.
I just, it was, people seemed, and I started kind of understanding what, you know, when things were called memorial bridges or memorial stadiums or memorial thisses,
you know, that most of that usually was tied to World War II or maybe World War I.
And I, the MSC has, you know, just had a fond place in my heart, I think.
In general, describe the A&M student body when you were here.
